nd 14 if they were 1s, but they are 0s.\n         - So the only way to include 8 is the term (a & ~b & ~c & ~d). \n         - The only way to include 12 is the term (a & b & ~c & ~d).\n         - Actually, (8, 12) can be grouped if we use 8, 12, 10, 14 or 8, 12, 9, 13. But 9, 10, 13, 14 are all 0. \n         - Let's look at the 1s again. 2, 7, 15. \n         - 2 (0010) + 3 (0011) = ~a & ~b & c\n         - 7 (0111) + 15 (1111) + 11 (1011) + 3 (0011) = c & d\n         - 8 (1000) + 12 (1100) = a & ~c & ~d\n         - Check: 8 is 1000. 12 is 1100. (8,12) is a & ~c & ~d. Let's check the bits: a is 1, c is 0, d is 0. b can be 0 or 1. This covers 1000 and 1100. Correct.\n         - So SOP = (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d) | (a & ~c & ~d).\n\n4. **POS (Product of Sums)**:\n   - We group the 0s and Xs to find the SOP of the complement, then invert.\n   - 0s: 0, 1, 4, 5, 6, 9, 10, 13, 14. Xs: 3, 8, 11, 12.\n   - Grouping 0s and Xs:\n     - (0, 1, 4, 5) -> ~c & ~d is wrong. (0,1,4,5) is ~a & ~c. (0,1,4,5) are 0000, 0001, 0100, 0101. Common: a=0, c=0. So ~a & ~c.\n     - (4, 5, 6, 7)? No, 7 is 1. (4, 5, 6) is not a power of 2. \n     - (6, 14, 10, 2)? No, 2 is 1. \n     - (13, 14, 9, 10, 15, 11, 8, 12)? 15 and 11 are 1s. \n     - Let's group 0s:\n       - (0, 1, 4, 5) -> ~a & ~c\n       - (6, 14) -> b & c & ~d\n       - (9, 10, 13, 14) -> a & ~c & d is wrong. (9,10,13,14) is a=1 and (c=0, d=1) or (c=1, d=0)? No. \n       - Let's try again. 0s: {0, 1, 4, 5, 6, 9, 10, 13, 14}. Xs: {3, 8, 11, 12}.\n       - Group 1: (0, 1, 4, 5) -> ~a & ~c\n       - Group 2: (9, 10, 13, 14, 8, 11, 12) - No, 11 is X, 15 is 1. \n       - Group 3: (13, 14, 9, 8)? 8 is X, 9 is 0, 13 is 0, 14 is 0. (8, 9, 12, 13) -> a & ~c. No, 8,9,12,13 are 1000, 1001, 1100, 1101. Common: a=1, c=0. So a & ~c.\n       - Group 4: (6, 14, 4, 12)? 4 is 0, 6 is 0, 12 is X, 14 is 0. (4,6,12,14) is b & ~d. Let's check: 4(0100), 6(0110), 12(1100), 14(1110). Common: b=1, d=0. So b & ~d.\n       - Group 5: (1, 9, 3, 11)? 1 is 0, 9 is 0, 3 is X, 11 is X. (1,3,9,11) is ~b & d. Let's check: 1(0001), 3(0011), 9(1001), 11(1011). Common: b=0, d=1. So ~b & d.\n       - Group 6: (10, 14, 8, 12)? 10(1010), 14(1110), 8(1000), 12(1100). Common: a=1, d=0. So a & ~d.\n       - Let's re-group 0s: {0,1,4,5,6,9,10,13,14} + Xs {3,8,11,12}\n         - (0,1,4,5) -> ~a & ~c\n         - (4,5,6,7) - No, 7 is 1. \n         - (4,5,12,13) -> b & ~c. (4:0100, 5:0101, 12:1100, 13:1101). Correct. \n         - (6,14,4,12) -> b & ~d. (4:0100, 6:0110, 12:1100, 14:1110). Correct. \n         - (9,10,13,14,8,11,12,15)? No. \n         - (8,9,10,11,12,13,14,15) is a. But 15 and 11 are 1s. \n         - Let's use the 1s/Xs to find POS by finding the 0s' SOP and inverting.\n         - 0s: {0,1,4,5,6,9,10,13,14}. Xs: {3,8,11,12}.\n         - (0,1,4,5) -> ~a & ~c\n         - (6,14,4,12) -> b & ~d\n         - (9,10,13,14,8,11,12,15)? No. \n         - (9,10,13,14) -> a & ~c & d? No. 9(1001), 10(1010), 13(1101), 14(1110). This is not a power of 2. \n         - Let's look at 0s again: 0,1,4,5,6,9,10,13,14.\n         - (0,1) -> ~a & ~b & ~c\n         - (4,5,6) -> Not a power of 2. \n         - (9,10,13,14) -> Not a power of 2. \n         - (1,9) -> ~b & ~c & d? No. 1(0001), 9(1001). Common: ~b & ~c & d. \n         - (10,14) -> a & c & ~d. 10(1010), 14(1110). Common: a=1, c=1, d=0. \n         - Let's try: f(a,b,c,d) = (a+c)*(b+d)*(...) - No. \n\n         - Let's use the 1s/Xs to define the 0s:\n           - 1s/Xs are {2,3,7,8,11,12,15}\n           - SOP for 1s: (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d) | (a & ~c & ~d)\n           - POS is the dual. If f = (term1) | (term2) | (term3), then f' = (term1') & (term2') & (term3').\n           - However, that's for the complement. We want the minimal POS for the original function.\n           - Let's find the 0s again: 0,1,4,5,6,9,10,13,14. Xs: 3,8,11,12.\n           - Grouping 0s: \n             - (0, 1, 4, 5) -> ~a & ~c\n             - (6, 14, 4, 12) -> b & ~d\n             - (9, 13, 1, 5) -> ~c & d? No. 1(0001), 5(0101), 9(1001), 13(1101). Common: ~c & d. (Check: 1:0001, 5:0101, 9:1001, 13:1101. Yes!)\n             - (10, 14, 8, 12) -> a & ~d? No, 10(1010), 14(1110), 8(1000), 12(1100). Common: a=1, d=0. So a & ~d.\n             - (0, 1, 8, 9) -> ~b & ~c. (Check: 0:0000, 1:0001, 8:1000, 9:1001. Yes!)\n             - (4, 5, 6, 7)? No, 7 is 1. \n             - Let's try grouping 0s: \n               - (0,1,4,5) -> ~a & ~c\n               - (1,5,9,13) -> ~c & d\n               - (10,14,8,12) -> a & ~d\n               - (6,14,4,12) -> b & ~d\n               - (0,1,8,9) -> ~b & ~c\n             - Wait, let's simplify the 0s: \n               - 0,1,4,5,6,8,9,10,12,13,14\n               - Group A: (0,1,4,5) -> ~a & ~c\n               - Group B: (8,9,12,13) -> a & ~c\n               - Group C: (0,1,8,9) -> ~b & ~c\n               - Group D: (4,5,6,7)? No. (4,5,12,13) -> b & ~c\n               - Group E: (6,14,4,12) -> b & ~d\n               - Group F: (10,14,8,12) -> a & ~d\n               - Group G: (1,5,9,13) -> ~c & d\n               - Let's combine: (~a & ~c) | (a & ~c) | (~b & ~c) | (b & ~c) = ~c.\n               - If ~c is 0, then the function is 1. But 2 is 1 (0010) and 7 is 1 (0111). So c must be 1 for those. \n               - If c=1, the function is 1 if (a,b,c,d) is (0,0,1,0) or (0,1,1,1) or (1,1,1,1).\n               - Let's re-examine the 0s: 0,1,4,5,6,9,10,13,14. \n               - Grouping 0s: \n                 - (0,1,4,5) -> ~a & ~c\n                 - (8,9,12,13) -> a & ~c\n                 - (1,5,9,13) -> ~c & d\n                 - (10,14,8,12) -> a & ~d\n                 - (6,14,4,12) -> b & ~d\n                 - (0,1,8,9) -> ~b & ~c\n                 - (4,5,6,7)? No. \n                 - (6,14,10,2)? No. \n                 - (0,4,8,12) -> ~c & ~d. (0:0000, 4:0100, 8:1000, 12:1100. Yes!)\n                 - Let's see: (0,1,4,5,8,9,12,13) is (~c). \n                 - 0,1,4,5,8,9,12,13 are all 0. So ~c is part of the 0s. \n                 - The remaining 0s are 6, 10, 14. \n                 - 6(0110), 10(1010), 14(1110). \n                 - Group (6,14) -> b & c & ~d\n                 - Group (10,14) -> a & c & ~d\n                 - Group (6,14,10,2)? No, 2 is 1.\n                 - (6,14,10,2) is not possible. But (6,14) and (10,14) can be grouped with (2,10) and (2,6) if 2 was 0. \n                 - So 0s are: ~c | (b & c & ~d) | (a & c & ~d) = ~c | (c & ~d & (a | b)) = ~c | (~d & (a | b)).\n                 - Let's check: \n                   - If c=0, output is 0. (Covers 0,1,4,5,8,9,12,13). Correct.\n                   - If c=1 and d=0 and (a=1 or b=1), output is 0. (Covers 6:0110, 10:1010, 14:1110). Correct.\n                   - All other cases: \n                     - 2: 0010 -> c=1, d=0, a=0, b=0. (Not 0). Correct.\n                     - 3: 0011 -> X. Correct.\n                     - 7: 0111 -> c=1, d=1. (Not 0). Correct.\n                     - 11: 1011 -> X. Correct.\n                     - 15: 1111 -> c=1, d=1. (Not 0). Correct.\n                 - So the 0s are: ~c | (a & c & ~d) | (b & c & ~d).\n                 - The 1s are the complement: ~(~c | (c & ~d & (a | b))) = c & ~(c & ~d & (a | b)) = c & (~c | d | ~(a | b)) = c & (d | (~a & ~b)) = (c & d) | (c & ~a & ~b).\n                 - This is exactly the SOP we found earlier: (c & d) | (~a & ~b & c).\n                 - Now we need the POS form. The 0s are ~c | (a & c & ~d) | (b & c & ~d).\n                 - POS is the product of the sums of the 0s: (c) & (a' + c + d) & (b' + c + d)? No, that's not right. \n                 - Let's use the 0s: 0s = {~c | (a & c & ~d) | (b & c & ~d)} is not a POS. \n                 - A POS form is (sum1) & (sum2) & ...\n                 - Let's find the 0s' minimal SOP and then negate it.\n                 - 0s SOP: ~c | (a & c & ~d) | (b & c & ~d). \n                 - Actually, the 0s are: ~c | (a & ~d) | (b & ~d) is not quite right. \n                 - Let's re-group the 0s: \n                   - (0,1,4,5,8,9,12,13) -> ~c\n                   - (6,14,4,12) -> b & ~d\n                   - (10,14,8,12) -> a & ~d\n                   - So 0s = ~c | (b & ~d) | (a & ~d) = ~c | (~d & (a | b)).\n                 - To get POS, we use the 1s: f = (c & d) | (c & ~a & ~b) = c & (d | (~a & ~b)).\n                 - The POS form of (d | (~a & ~b)) is (d | ~a) & (d | ~b).\n                 - So f = c & (a' + d) & (b' + d).\n                 - Let's check f = c & (a' + d) & (b' + d):\n                   - 2: 0010 -> 1 & (1+0) & (1+0) = 1. Correct.\n                   - 7: 0111 -> 1 & (1+1) & (0+1) = 1. Correct.\n                   - 15: 1111 -> 1 & (0+1) & (0+1) = 1. Correct.\n                   - 0: 0000 -> 0 & ... = 0. Correct.\n                   - 6: 0110 -> 1 & (1+0) & (0+0) = 0. Correct.\n                   - 10: 1010 -> 1 & (0+0) & (1+0) = 0. Correct.\n                   - 14: 1110 -> 1 & (0+0) & (0+0) = 0. Correct.\n                   - 13: 1101 -> 0 & ... = 0. Correct.\n\n5. **Final Expressions**:\n   - out_sop = (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d) | (a & ~c & ~d) (Wait, let's re-check if (a & ~c & ~d) is needed in SOP).\n     - If we use (c & d) | (~a & ~b & c), does it cover all 1s? 2, 7, 15. \n     - 2: 0010. (~0 & ~0 & 1) = 1. Yes.\n     - 7: 0111. (1 & 1) = 1. Yes.\n     - 15: 1111. (1 & 1) = 1. Yes.\n     - Does it include 8 (1000)? 8: (1 & 0 & 0) | (0 & 0) = 0. Correct.\n     - Does it include 12 (1100)? 12: (1 & 0 & 0) | (0 & 0) = 0. Correct.\n     - So SOP = (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d).\n   - out_pos = c & (~a | d) & (~b | d).\n\n6. **Wait!** The problem asks for **minimum** SOP and **minimum** POS. \n   - SOP: (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d). (2 terms)\n   - POS: c & (~a | d) & (~b | d). (3 sums)\n   - Let's check if there is a smaller SOP. We have 3 minterms. Can we cover them with 2 terms? Yes, (2,3) and (3,7,11,15). We used 3 as a don't care. \n   - Is there any other way? (2,3) and (7,15)? (2,3) is ~a & ~b & c. (7,15) is b & c & d. \n   - Let's check (7,15): 0111 and 1111. Common is b=1, c=1, d=1. So b & c & d. \n   - (2,3) is ~a & ~b & c. \n   - (3,7,11,15) is c & d. \n   - Compare (b & c & d) with (c & d). (c & d) is smaller (fewer literals) and covers more. \n   - So SOP = (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d).\n   - Let's check if there's a smaller POS. We have 3 terms. Can we have 2? \n     - f = c & (d | (~a & ~b)).\n     - (d | (~a & ~b)) is a single term in SOP, but in POS it is (d | ~a) & (d | ~b).\n     - So 3 terms is the minimum for POS.\n\n7. **Final Check of bit order**: \n   - 7 is a=0, b=1, c=1, d=1. This matches the binary 0111. \n   - The inputs are a, b, c, d (a is MSB, d is LSB).\n   - 2 is 0010 (a=0, b=0, c=1, d=0). \n   - 15 is 1111 (a=1, b=1, c=1, d=1). \n\n8. **Implementation Details**:\n   - `out_sop = (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d);` \n   - `out_pos = c & (~a | d) & (~b | d);` \n   - Use `logic` for all. \n   - Use `always @(*)` for combinational logic. \n   - Advice to avoid syntax error: Ensure all `~` are correctly placed and parentheses are used to avoid precedence issues. In Verilog, `~` has higher precedence than `&` and `|`.\n",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic a,\n    input  logic b,\n    input  logic c,\n    input  logic d,\n    output logic out_sop,\n    output logic out_pos\n);\n\n    // Combinational logic for out_sop (Minimum Sum-of-Products)\n    // Minterms: 2 (0010), 7 (0111), 15 (1111)\n    // Don't-cares: 3 (0011), 8 (1000), 11 (1011), 12 (1100)\n    // Group 1: (2, 3) -> ~a & ~b & c\n    // Group 2: (3, 7, 11, 15) -> c & d\n    // SOP = (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d)\n    always @(*) begin\n        out_sop = (~a & ~b & c) | (c & d);\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic for out_pos (Minimum Product-of-Sums)\n    // Derived from SOP: c & (d | (~a & ~b))\n    // Using distributive law: c & (d | ~a) & (d | ~b)\n    // POS = c & (~a | d) & (~b | d)\n    always @(*) begin\n        out_pos = c & (~a | d) & (~b | d);\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
